.El
.Sh PERSONALITIES
Personalities are
.Nm Ns 's
answer to
.Sy alias ll='ls -l' :
a structured, inheritable, introspectable way to have multiple
.Dq modes
for listing files, without shell configuration.
A personality is a named bundle of flags and settings, activated
either by the name
.Nm
is invoked under (via an
.Sy argv[0]
symlink), by the
.Fl p Ns / Ns Fl -personality
flag, by the
.Ev LX_PERSONALITY
environment variable, or by the compiled-in default when bare
.Nm
is run.
.Pp
Resolution precedence (highest to lowest):
.Fl p
flag,
.Sy argv[0]
symlink name,
.Ev LX_PERSONALITY ,
compiled-in default
.Pq Cm lx .
When
.Nm
is invoked by its own name, the
.Sy argv[0]
step is skipped so that
.Ev LX_PERSONALITY
can take effect.
An unknown name from
.Fl p
or
.Ev LX_PERSONALITY
is an error; an unknown
.Sy argv[0]
name falls through silently.
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl p , Fl -personality Ns = Ns Ar NAME
Apply a named personality for this invocation.
Equivalent to invoking
.Nm
via an
.Sy argv[0]
symlink with the same name.
.El
.Pp
Compiled-in personalities:
.Bl -tag -width "Cm tree" -offset indent -compact
.It Cm lx
the default, used when
.Nm
is invoked as itself.
.It Cm ll
long view equivalent to
.Sy lx -l ,
with VCS status and directories grouped first.
.It Cm la
like
.Cm ll ,
plus hidden files.
.It Cm lll
tier-3 long view with header, all timestamps, and extra metadata
columns.
.It Cm tree
recursive tree view with directories first.
.It Cm ls
tries to mimic POSIX
.Xr ls 1 .
.El
.Pp
Additional personalities may be defined in the config file.
Every CLI flag has a corresponding config key, so a personality
definition is simply the flags you would type on the command line,
spelled out as TOML.
Personalities support inheritance
.Pq Sy inherits = \(dqNAME\(dq
to build on another personality's settings, and may select a theme
.Pq Sy theme = \(dqNAME\(dq :
.Bd -literal -offset indent
[personality.work]
inherits = "ll"
ignore = "*.tmp|*.bak"
time-style = "long-iso"
theme = "catppuccin-mocha"
.Ed
.Pp
When
.Nm
is invoked via a symlink whose name matches a personality, that
personality is applied automatically.
For example, if
.Sy ll
is a symlink to
.Nm
on your
.Ev PATH ,
running
.Sy ll
is equivalent to
.Sy lx -p ll .
This is the recommended way to use personalities in daily work \(em
create the symlinks once, and never type
.Fl p
again.
.Pp
For the full syntax, including every personality setting key, the
inheritance semantics, and the conditional
.Sy [[when]]
block vocabulary for environment-based overrides, see the
.Sx PERSONALITIES
section of
.Xr lxconfig.toml 5 .
.Sh VCS INTEGRATION
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl -vcs Ns = Ns Ar BACKEND
Select the VCS backend.
.Ar BACKEND
is
.Cm auto ,
.Cm git ,
.Cm jj ,
or
.Cm none .
Default:
.Cm auto
(prefers jj if
.Pa .jj/
exists, falls back to git).
The
.Cm jj
backend requires
.Nm
to be built with the
.Sy jj
feature flag.
.It Fl -vcs-status
Show per-file VCS status column.
The column header shows the active backend:
.Sy Git
or
.Sy JJ .
Status characters:
.Sq -
not modified,
.Sq M
modified,
.Sq A
added (jj) /
.Sq N
new (git),
.Sq D
deleted,
.Sq R
renamed,
.Sq C
copied,
.Sq I
ignored,
.Sq U
untracked,
.Sq \&!
conflicted.
git shows two columns (staged + unstaged); when both are the same,
they collapse into one character.
jj shows two columns: change status
.Pq Sq @ No vs Sq @-
and tracking status
.Pq U untracked, I ignored, space = tracked .
.It Fl -vcs-ignore
Hide files ignored by VCS and VCS metadata directories
.Pq Pa .git , Pa .jj .
Works with both git and jj backends.
.It Fl -vcs-repos
Show a per-directory VCS repository indicator column.
For each directory, shows
.Sq G
(git repo),
.Sq J
(jj repo), or
.Sq -
(not a repo).
Git repos also show the current branch name.
Useful for scanning workspace directories containing multiple
repositories.
.El
.Pp
Note: the legacy
.Fl -git
and
.Fl -git-ignore
flags have been removed.
Use
.Fl -vcs-status
and
.Fl -vcs-ignore
instead.
.Sh CONFIGURATION
.Nm
reads a TOML configuration file from these locations (first found
wins):
.Bl -enum -offset indent -compact
.It
.Ev LX_CONFIG
\(em explicit path
.It
.Pa ~/.lxconfig.toml
.It
.Pa $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/lx/config.toml
.It
.Pa ~/Library/Application Support/lx/config.toml
(macOS)
.El
.Pp
Run
.Sy lx --init-config
to generate a commented starter file.
.Pp
The config file includes a
.Sy version
field to track the schema version.
The current version is
.Sy \(dq0.5\(dq .
If you have a legacy config from an earlier version, run
.Sy lx --upgrade-config
to migrate it (migrations from 0.1 through 0.4 are all supported; a
.Pa .bak
of the original is saved automatically).
.Pp
For the full config file format \(em every section type, every key,
the conditional
.Sy [[when]]
block syntax for environment-based personality overrides, and the
complete theme/style/class vocabulary \(em see
.Xr lxconfig.toml 5 .
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl -show-config
Show a coloured summary of the active configuration and exit.
.It Fl -init-config
Generate a commented starter config file at
.Pa ~/.lxconfig.toml .
.It Fl -upgrade-config
Upgrade a legacy config file to the current format.
.It Fl -save-as Ns = Ns Ar NAME
Save the CLI flags from this invocation as a named personality in
.Pa conf.d/ Ns Ar NAME Ns Pa .toml .
The saved definition inherits from the active personality and
contains only the flags you typed on this command line.
If the target file already exists, the previous file is backed up
with a
.Pa .bak
suffix.
Exits after saving without listing files.
.El
.Pp
The
.Fl -dump-*
flags output copy-pasteable TOML definitions.
Each accepts an optional
.Sy = Ns Ar NAME
to dump a single definition, or dumps all when used bare:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl -dump-class Ns Op = Ns Ar NAME
Dump file-type class definitions.
.It Fl -dump-format Ns Op = Ns Ar NAME
Dump column format definitions.
.It Fl -dump-personality Ns Op = Ns Ar NAME
Dump personality definitions (before inheritance merging).
.It Fl -dump-theme Ns Op = Ns Ar NAME
Dump theme definitions.
.It Fl -dump-style Ns Op = Ns Ar NAME
Dump style definitions.
.El
.Sh DROP-IN DIRECTORY
After loading the main config file,
.Nm
scans a
.Pa conf.d/
directory for additional TOML fragments.
Each
.Pa *.toml
file in the directory is loaded in alphabetical order and merged
into the configuration.
Later files override earlier ones by name.
.Pp
The drop-in directory is searched at:
.Bl -enum -offset indent -compact
.It
The parent directory of the main config file, plus
.Pa conf.d/
.It
.Pa $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/lx/conf.d/
(default:
.Pa ~/.config/lx/conf.d/ )
.It
.Pa ~/Library/Application Support/lx/conf.d/
(macOS)
.El
.Pp
Drop-in files do not need a
.Sy version
field.
They may contain any combination of
.Sy [theme.*] ,
.Sy [style.*] ,
.Sy [class] ,
.Sy [personality.*] ,
and
.Sy [format.*]
sections.
.Pp
.Nm
ships with a library of curated themes in the
.Pa themes/
directory of the source tree \(em copy any of them to
.Pa conf.d/
to activate.
.Sh SHELL COMPLETIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl -completions Ns = Ns Ar SHELL
Generate shell completion script for
.Ar SHELL
and write it to stdout.
.Ar SHELL
is one of
.Cm bash ,
.Cm zsh ,
.Cm fish ,
.Cm elvish ,
or
.Cm powershell .
.El
.Pp
Quick activation for the current session:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
# bash
source <(lx --completions bash)

# zsh
source <(lx --completions zsh)

# fish
lx --completions fish | source
.Ed
.Pp
Or save to the standard location for permanent installation, e.g.:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
lx --completions bash > ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions/lx
lx --completions zsh  > ~/.zfunc/_lx
lx --completions fish > ~/.config/fish/completions/lx.fish
.Ed
.Pp
(For zsh,
.Pa ~/.zfunc
must be in your
.Ev fpath . )
.Pp
For
.Cm bash ,
.Cm zsh ,
and
.Cm fish ,
the generated script also registers completions for every
personality symlink found in
.Ev PATH
that points to the
.Nm
binary.
For example, if
.Pa ll
and
.Pa tree
are symlinks to
.Nm ,
tab completion works for those names too.
Regenerate completions after creating or removing personality
symlinks.
.Pp
.Cm elvish
and
.Cm powershell
completions cover the
.Nm
command only.
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Ev LX_CONFIG
Explicit path to the config file.
.It Ev LX_DEBUG
Enable debug logging.
Set to
.Sy 1
for debug,
.Sy trace
for trace level.
.It Ev LX_GRID_ROWS
Minimum rows before the grid-details view activates.
Also settable as
.Sy grid-rows
in a personality definition (config takes precedence).
.It Ev LX_ICON_SPACING
Number of spaces between an icon and its filename.
Also settable as
.Sy icon-spacing
in a personality definition (config takes precedence).
.It Ev LX_PERSONALITY
Session-level personality selection.
Equivalent to
.Sy -p Ar NAME
but lower in precedence than both
.Fl p
and
.Sy argv[0]
symlink dispatch.
Useful for setting a default personality per terminal or shell
session.
.It Ev LS_COLORS
Standard file-type colour scheme.
.It Ev COLUMNS
Override terminal width.
.It Ev TIME_STYLE
Default timestamp style (overridden by
.Fl -time-style ) .
.It Ev NO_COLOR
Disable colours.
See
.Lk https://no-color.org/ .
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Bl -tag -width "0" -compact
.It 0
Success.
.It 1
Runtime error (I/O error during operation).
.It 3
Options error (invalid command-line arguments).
.El
.Sh FEATURES
.Nm
has optional feature flags that control which VCS backends are
compiled in.
These are selected at build time with
.Sy cargo build --features .
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Sy git Pq default
Git support via the
.Sy git2
crate.
.It Sy jj Pq opt-in
Jujutsu support via the
.Sy jj-lib
crate.
Adds approximately 5 MB to the binary size.
Build with:
.Sy cargo build --features jj .
.El
